2026-06-24 | Count ZigZag Arrays

	Question
Return the number of valid ZigZag arrays modulo 10^9+7.
	Key Observation
For any three consecutive elements:
		a, b, c
If:
		a < b
then to avoid
		a < b < c
we must have
		c < b
Similarly, if:
		a > b
then to avoid
		a > b > c
we must have
		c > b
So after an increasing step, the next step must be decreasing.
After a decreasing step, the next step must be increasing.
	State Definition
Let:
		m = r - l + 1
Compress values to:
		0 ... m-1
Define:
		up[v]
	= number of valid arrays ending at value v
	  whose last movement was increasing
		down[v]
	= number of valid arrays ending at value v
	  whose last movement was decreasing
	Base Case (Length = 2)
For every pair:
		a < b
	contributes to
		up[b]
For every pair:
		a > b
	contributes to
		down[b]
	Transition
To create an UP state ending at x:
		previous movement must be DOWN
		previous value must be smaller than x
So:
		newUp[x]
		=
		sum of down[y]
		for y < x
To create a DOWN state ending at x:
		previous movement must be UP
		previous value must be greater than x
So:
		newDown[x]
		=
		sum of up[y]
		for y > x
Using prefix sums these transitions become O(1) per value.
	Time Complexity
		O(n × (r-l+1))
	Space Complexity
		O(r-l+1)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    static const int MOD = 1000000007;
    int zigZagArrays(int n, int l, int r) {
        int m = r - l + 1;
        if(n == 1)
            return m;
        vector<long long> up(m, 0);
        vector<long long> down(m, 0);
        for(int a = 0; a < m; a++) {
            for(int b = 0; b < m; b++) {
                if(a == b) continue;
                if(a < b)
                    up[b] = (up[b] + 1) % MOD;
                else
                    down[b] = (down[b] + 1) % MOD;
            }
        }
        for(int len = 3; len <= n; len++) {
            vector<long long> prefUp(m + 1, 0);
            vector<long long> prefDown(m + 1, 0);
            for(int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
                prefUp[i + 1] =
                    (prefUp[i] + up[i]) % MOD;
                prefDown[i + 1] =
                    (prefDown[i] + down[i]) % MOD;
            }
            vector<long long> newUp(m, 0);
            vector<long long> newDown(m, 0);
            for(int x = 0; x < m; x++) {
                newUp[x] = prefDown[x];
                newDown[x] =
                    (prefUp[m] - prefUp[x + 1] + MOD)
                    % MOD;
            }
            up = move(newUp);
            down = move(newDown);
        }
        long long ans = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
            ans = (ans + up[i] + down[i]) % MOD;
        }
        return (int)ans;
    }
};
	Edge Cases
•	n = 1
		Every value in [l,r] is valid.
		Answer = r-l+1
•	If only one value exists in the range:
		l = r
	and n > 1
		Answer = 0
	because adjacent elements cannot be equal.
	Key Insight
The condition "no three consecutive elements are strictly increasing or strictly decreasing" forces the comparison signs between consecutive elements to alternate:
		< > < > ...
	or
		> < > < ...
This reduces the problem to tracking only the last value and the last movement direction, enabling an O(n × (r-l+1)) DP solution.
